<p>There is a folder on my computer with files like <code>script.js</code> and <code>data.json</code> in it.<br> In <code>script.js</code> there is a variable called <code>data</code>.<br> Content of <code>data.json</code> is like:    </p>  <pre><code>[   { "key_11" : "value_11",     "key_12" : "value_12" },   { "key_21" : "value_21",     "key_22" : "value_22" },   { "key_31" : "value_31",     "key_32" : "value_32" } ] </code></pre>  <p>I need to assign whole <code>data.json</code> content to var <code>data</code> as its value like:</p>  <pre><code>var data = [   { "key_11" : "value_11",     "key_12" : "value_12" },   { "key_21" : "value_21",     "key_22" : "value_22" },   { "key_31" : "value_31",     "key_32" : "value_32" } ]; </code></pre>  <p>(variable <code>data</code> here becomes an array with 3 Object-elements).</p>  <p>I do</p>  <pre><code>var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();   xhr.open("GET", "data.json", true);   xhr.send(); var data = (xhr.status == 200)? "" : xhr.responseText; </code></pre>  <p>but it fails with error</p>  <pre><code>Cross origin requests are only supported for protocol schemes: http, data, chrome, chrome-extension, https, chrome-extension-resource. </code></pre>  <p>(in Google Chrome).</p>  <p>How can I properly do this without using JQuery?</p>